-- Regulations & Safety course articles (basic tier)

INSERT INTO public.courses (module, content_type, title, slug, description, body, duration_minutes, tier_required, category, sort_order, published, published_at) VALUES
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'Hunter Safety and Ethics in the Field',
  'hunter-safety-ethics',
  'Core principles of safe firearm handling, treestand safety, ethical harvest, and responsible behavior in the field.',
  E'# Hunter Safety and Ethics in the Field\n\nHunting accident rates have dropped more than 50% over the last two decades, largely thanks to mandatory hunter education programs. But the numbers still aren''t zero — and nearly 80% of incidents trace back to a preventable human decision. This guide covers the safety fundamentals and ethical principles that every hunter should internalize before heading afield.\n\n## The Four Rules of Firearm Safety\n\nEvery hunter education course teaches the same four rules, often remembered with the acronym **ACTT**:\n\n1. **Always treat every firearm as if it were loaded.** There is no such thing as an unloaded gun during field handling.\n2. **Control the muzzle at all times.** Never point a firearm at anything you are not willing to destroy. In the field, this means muzzle-down or skyward when crossing terrain.\n3. **Be certain of your target and what is beyond it.** Failure to properly identify a target accounts for 37% of firearm-related hunting incidents — it is the single leading cause.\n4. **Keep your finger outside the trigger guard until ready to shoot.** Most unintentional discharges happen because a finger enters the trigger guard prematurely.\n\nThese rules are not suggestions. They are redundant layers of protection — if you violate one, the others still prevent a tragedy. If you violate two, you''re relying on luck.\n\n## Firearm Safety in the Field\n\nThe controlled environment of a shooting range is nothing like the reality of hunting terrain. Here is where the rules get tested:\n\n- **Crossing obstacles**: Unload your firearm before crossing a fence, creek, or steep slope. Hand it across unloaded, action open.\n- **Zone of fire**: In a group, each hunter must have a designated arc of safe shooting. Everyone must know where everyone else is at all times.\n- **Vehicles**: Firearms should be unloaded and cased during transport. A loaded rifle leaning against a truck bed is an accident waiting to happen.\n- **Low light**: Dawn and dusk are when most hunting occurs — and when target identification is hardest. If you cannot positively identify the animal and confirm what is behind it, do not shoot.\n\n### Blaze Orange Requirements\n\nMost western states require fluorescent orange during firearm seasons:\n\n| State | Requirement |\n|-------|-------------|\n| Colorado | 500 sq. in. of solid fluorescent orange on head, chest, and back |\n| Wyoming | One exterior article of fluorescent orange |\n| Montana | 400 sq. in. above the waist + orange hat |\n| Idaho | 36 sq. in. of fluorescent orange on head, chest, or back |\n| Utah | 400 sq. in. of hunter orange |\n| Arizona | Not required (recommended) |\n| Nevada | Not required (recommended) |\n\nArchery-only seasons generally do not require orange, but wearing it near roads and trailheads is smart practice.\n\n## Treestand Safety\n\nTreestand falls are now the leading cause of hunting injuries in many states — more common than firearm incidents. The numbers are sobering:\n\n- **3,000–4,000 treestand injuries** occur annually in the U.S.\n- **80% of falls** happen during the climb up or down, not while seated.\n- **95% of serious injuries** involve hunters who were not wearing a harness.\n- **81% of victims require surgery**; 59% involve spinal fractures.\n\n### The Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Use a full-body fall-arrest harness (FBFAHS).** Single-strap belts and chest harnesses no longer meet TMA safety standards.\n2. **Connect before you leave the ground.** Use a lineman''s belt during the climb, then switch to the tether at the platform.\n3. **Keep the tether short.** It should keep you in your seat, not catch you after a six-foot fall.\n4. **Inspect your gear annually.** Strap rot, metal fatigue, and frayed connections are invisible killers.\n5. **Tell someone your stand location.** If you fall and are suspended in a harness, suspension trauma can set in within 20 minutes.\n\n## Fair Chase Ethics\n\nThe Boone and Crockett Club — the oldest conservation organization in North America, founded in 1887 — defines fair chase as:\n\n> "The ethical, sportsmanlike, and lawful pursuit and taking of any free-ranging wild game animal in a manner that does not give the hunter an improper or unfair advantage over the game animals."\n\nFair chase is not just about following the law. Legality sets the floor — ethics set the ceiling. A fair chase hunter:\n\n- **Measures success by the quality of the chase**, not the size of the rack or the number of animals taken.\n- **Takes only shots within their confirmed effective range.** If environmental conditions (wind, mirage, distance) create doubt, the shot is not taken.\n- **Makes full use of harvested animals.** Wanton waste is both illegal and deeply unethical.\n- **Does not use technology for unfair advantage** — real-time drone scouting, spotlighting, and shooting from motorized vehicles all violate fair chase principles.\n\n### Shot Placement as an Ethical Obligation\n\nThe most ethical shot is broadside or slightly quartering-away, targeting the heart and lung zone. Quartering-toward, frontal, and steep downward angle shots dramatically increase wounding risk. If you are not confident the shot will kill cleanly, let the animal walk. There will be other opportunities.\n\n## Leave No Trace in Hunting Camp\n\nHunters operate in wild places at low densities, often in areas rarely visited by others. The condition of those places directly affects future access — for you and every hunter who follows.\n\n**Key principles applied to hunting:**\n\n- **Pack out everything**: food wrappers, spent brass, zip ties, flagging tape, game bags. Spent shells are the most commonly left litter at hunting camps.\n- **Gut piles**: Move them at least 200 feet from water sources, camps, and high-traffic trails.\n- **Human waste**: Dig a cathole 6–8 inches deep, at least 200 feet from water.\n- **Remove your gear**: Take down trail cameras, stands, and flagging tape at the end of the season. Do not leave permanent fixtures on public land.\n- **Campfires**: Use existing fire rings only. Check current fire restrictions — bans are common during September and October elk seasons in CO, MT, WY, and ID.\n- **Food and meat storage**: In bear country (CO, WY, MT, ID), use bear canisters or proper hang systems. Improperly stored food attracts bears that then get destroyed by wildlife agencies.\n\nA single irresponsible camp or confrontation with a hiker can generate years of anti-hunting advocacy from other public land users. Stewardship is not optional — it is how we protect access for the next generation.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. If you haven''t completed a hunter education course, do it now. One certification is valid in all 50 states.\n2. Practice firearm handling at the range until the four rules are muscle memory.\n3. If you use a treestand, invest in a quality full-body harness system and practice with it before the season.\n4. Read the fair chase statement at boone-crockett.org — it takes five minutes and will shape how you hunt for life.',
  10, 'basic', 'regulations-safety', 4, true, NOW()
),
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'Understanding Western State Hunting Regulations',
  'western-state-regulations',
  'How to read and interpret state regulation booklets — seasons, legal weapons, unit boundaries, harvest reporting, and CWD zones.',
  E'# Understanding Western State Hunting Regulations\n\nEvery western state publishes a regulation booklet — sometimes called a "brochure" — that governs when, where, and how you can hunt. These booklets are dense, they change every year, and misreading one can cost you a tag, a fine, or your hunting privileges. This guide teaches you how to navigate them.\n\n## Where to Find Official Regulations\n\nAlways start at the source. Regulation booklets are free, published online, and updated annually:\n\n| State | Agency | Where to Find Regulations |\n|-------|--------|---------------------------|\n| Colorado | Colorado Parks and Wildlife (CPW) | cpw.state.co.us |\n| Montana | Montana FWP | fwp.mt.gov/hunt/regulations |\n| Wyoming | Wyoming Game & Fish (WGFD) | wgfd.wyo.gov/regulations |\n| Idaho | Idaho Fish & Game (IDFG) | idfg.idaho.gov/rules |\n| Nevada | Nevada Dept. of Wildlife (NDOW) | ndow.org/rules-regulations |\n| Utah | Utah DWR | wildlife.utah.gov |\n| Arizona | Arizona Game & Fish (AZGFD) | azgfd.com/hunting/regulations |\n\n**Important**: Regulation booklets are "simplified statements of controlling law." They are not the full legal text. If something is ambiguous, the actual statute or administrative rule governs — not the booklet summary.\n\n## How to Read a Season Structure\n\nMost booklets organize information by species first, then by season type (archery, muzzleloader, rifle), then by Game Management Unit (GMU) or Hunt Area. Here is what each column typically means:\n\n- **Hunt Code**: An encoded string that tells you species, unit, season, and weapon. Colorado''s elk code "E-E-050-O1-R" means Elk, Early season, GMU 050, Season 1, Rifle.\n- **Dates**: Opening and closing day of the season. Some states split rifle into 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 4th seasons.\n- **Bag Limit**: What sex and class of animal you can harvest (e.g., "antlered deer" means bucks only).\n- **Legal Weapons**: What you can use during that season. Archery seasons restrict to bows; muzzleloader seasons have specific requirements for ignition type and projectile.\n- **Unit/Area**: The geographic boundary where the tag is valid. Always cross-reference with the unit boundary map.\n\n### Pro Tip for New Hunters\n\nRead the **General Regulations** section first — before diving into species-specific pages. General regs cover licensing requirements, shooting hours, blaze orange rules, wanton waste laws, and other rules that apply across all species and seasons.\n\n## Legal Shooting Hours\n\nThis is one of the most commonly misunderstood differences between states:\n\n| State | Big Game Shooting Hours |\n|-------|-------------------------|\n| Colorado | Half-hour before sunrise to half-hour after sunset |\n| Montana | Half-hour before sunrise to sunset |\n| Wyoming | Half-hour before sunrise to sunset |\n| Idaho | Half-hour before sunrise to sunset |\n| Nevada | Half-hour before sunrise to half-hour after sunset |\n| Utah | Sunrise to sunset |\n| Arizona | Half-hour before sunrise to sunset |\n\nNotice Utah''s window is significantly shorter — no grace period at either end. If you are used to hunting Colorado''s generous window, this catches people. When hunting near state lines, you must follow the regulations of the state you are physically in.\n\n## Tag Validation and Carcass Tagging\n\nMost western states require you to validate your tag immediately at the site of kill before moving the animal. This typically means:\n\n1. **Notch or punch** the date of kill on the tag (some states use tear-off tabs).\n2. **Attach the tag** to the carcass in a visible location.\n3. **Keep the tag attached** during transport until the animal reaches your home or a processor.\n\nFailure to tag before transport is a violation in every western state — even if you have a valid, unused tag in your pocket. The tag must be on the animal.\n\n## Mandatory Harvest Reporting\n\nReporting requirements vary significantly:\n\n| State | Reporting Required? | Deadline | Notes |\n|-------|---------------------|----------|-------|\n| Colorado | Yes, most big game | Varies by species | Check the brochure for your specific tag |\n| Wyoming | Partial | 10 days post-harvest | Mandatory for buck deer, bull elk, bighorn, moose |\n| Montana | No | N/A | Voluntary sampling program |\n| Idaho | Yes | 10 days post-harvest | All deer, elk, antelope, plus bighorn/moose/goat |\n| Nevada | Yes | 48 hours | All big game — one of the shortest windows |\n| Utah | Yes | 48 hours / Feb 15 max | Mandatory even if you did NOT harvest |\n| Arizona | Partial | Varies | Elk and antelope voluntary; check other species |\n\n**Utah catches people**: You must report even if you went home empty-handed. Failure to report a failed hunt is a violation.\n\n**Nevada''s 48-hour window** is tight. If you harvest in a remote canyon with no cell service, plan your exit to meet the deadline.\n\n## CWD Testing Zones\n\nChronic Wasting Disease is now confirmed in 36 U.S. states. Several western states have mandatory testing requirements in specific units:\n\n- **Colorado (2026)**: Mandatory CWD sample submission for elk harvested during rifle seasons in specific hunt codes. Check pages 41–52 of the Big Game Brochure.\n- **Wyoming**: Free testing statewide; mandatory in specific hunt areas (96, 97, 164, 70, and the National Elk Refuge).\n- **Idaho**: Mandatory testing in seven specific units including 63A; free of charge. Samples due within 10 days.\n- **Montana**: Voluntary statewide. CWD detected in 33% of hunt districts; 39% prevalence in white-tailed deer in the highest-affected areas.\n- **Utah**: 435 mule deer and 11 elk confirmed positive. Targeted sampling areas include Beaver, Box Elder, Cache, and La Sal units.\n- **Nevada and Arizona**: CWD has **not** been detected. No mandatory testing.\n\n### Interstate Transport\n\nNever transport whole deer or elk carcasses across state lines from CWD-positive areas. Most states prohibit importing brain, spinal cord, intact head, or spinal column from animals harvested in known CWD zones. This is also a federal issue under the Lacey Act.\n\n## Common Violations Hunters Don''t Realize They''re Committing\n\n1. **Shooting outside legal hours**: Especially common at last light. The act itself is the violation — intent does not matter.\n2. **Shooting the wrong animal**: Mistaking a doe for a buck, or the wrong species entirely. Self-report immediately — penalties are typically reduced for honest mistakes.\n3. **Not having your tag on your person**: You must carry your physical license and tag while hunting in all western states.\n4. **Wanton waste**: Failing to salvage edible meat is a misdemeanor in Colorado, carrying 15 license suspension points for big game.\n5. **Unintentional trespass**: "I didn''t see the sign" is not a defense. Use a mapping tool to verify land boundaries before you walk.\n6. **Failure to report harvest**: See the table above. Missing the deadline is a violation even if you harvested legally.\n\n### What Suspension Really Means\n\nAll 48 states in the Interstate Wildlife Violator Compact share suspension information. A license suspension in Colorado bars you from hunting in Wyoming, Montana, Idaho, and every other compact state until it is resolved. A serious poaching violation can cost $20,000–$50,000+ in fines, restitution, and legal fees — plus years of lost hunting.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Download the current regulation booklet for every state where you hold tags or plan to apply.\n2. Read the General Regulations section first — every time, every year.\n3. Use the Deadline Tracker to stay on top of application windows.\n4. When in doubt, call the local game warden or district office. They would rather answer a question than write a citation.',
  12, 'basic', 'regulations-safety', 5, true, NOW()
),
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'Backcountry First Aid for Hunters',
  'backcountry-first-aid',
  'Essential first aid knowledge for remote hunting trips — from lacerations and treestand falls to hypothermia, altitude sickness, and emergency evacuation.',
  E'# Backcountry First Aid for Hunters\n\nLacerations during field dressing are the most common backcountry hunting injury. Treestand falls cause more injuries than firearms. And the terrain western hunters operate in — steep, remote, often above 8,000 feet — amplifies the consequences of every mishap. This guide covers what you need to know and carry.\n\n## Building a Hunting-Specific First Aid Kit\n\nA generic drugstore kit will not cut it in the backcountry. Your kit should scale with trip remoteness and duration — a solo 10-day wilderness elk hunt demands more than a morning sit one mile from the truck.\n\n### Bleeding Control (Priority 1)\n- **Tourniquet** (CAT or SOFTT-W) — applied 2–3 inches above a wound with arterial bleeding\n- **Hemostatic gauze** (QuikClot or Celox combat gauze) — accelerates clotting in deep wounds\n- **Pressure dressing** (Israeli bandage or 4x4 sterile pads + elastic wrap)\n- **Vented chest seal** — for penetrating chest wounds from broadheads or branches\n- **Nitrile gloves** (multiple pairs)\n\n### Wound Care\n- **Irrigation syringe** (20 mL with 18-gauge tip) — forceful saline or clean water flush removes debris\n- **Wound closure**: Steri-Strips, butterfly closures, or medical super glue (Dermabond)\n- **Triple antibiotic ointment**\n- **Non-stick gauze pads** + cloth medical tape\n- **Blister kit** (Moleskin + Second Skin)\n\n### Structural\n- **SAM splint** — moldable aluminum/foam splint for ankles, wrists, and knees\n- **ACE elastic bandage** (2 rolls)\n\n### Medications\n- Ibuprofen 200 mg + acetaminophen 500 mg (alternate for pain management)\n- Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) for allergic reactions\n- Prescription oral antibiotics — ask your physician for a backcountry supply of Amoxicillin-clavulanate\n- Epinephrine auto-injector if you have known severe allergies\n\n### Thermal Protection\n- **Emergency bivvy** (SOL Escape Bivvy or similar) — far superior to a basic space blanket\n- **Chemical hand warmers** (4–6 packs)\n\n## Handling Lacerations in the Field\n\nCold hands, wet and bloody material, unfamiliar technique, and rushing — field dressing injuries happen because of exactly these conditions. When it happens:\n\n1. **Sit down immediately.** This lowers your heart rate and reduces blood pressure.\n2. **Apply direct pressure** with clean gauze for 10–15 minutes. Do not lift to check — this disrupts clot formation.\n3. **Bright red pulsating blood = arterial bleed.** Apply your tourniquet 2–3 inches above the wound without delay.\n4. **Once bleeding is controlled**, irrigate the wound thoroughly with your syringe to flush out debris and bacteria.\n5. **Close with Steri-Strips** if the wound edges come together cleanly and the cut is not deep.\n6. **Cover with a non-stick dressing** and secure with tape.\n7. **Watch for infection** over the following days: redness spreading from wound edges, warmth, swelling, pus, or red streaks tracking toward the body. Red streaks indicate spreading infection and require evacuation.\n\n### Broadhead Injuries\n\nTreat like a serious laceration with one critical rule: **do NOT remove an impaled broadhead in the field.** Stabilize it in place with bulky gauze padding and evacuate. Removing it can cause uncontrolled bleeding.\n\n## Hypothermia\n\nMost hypothermia cases occur at temperatures **above freezing**. The lethal combination is wet clothing + wind + fatigue — all common during backcountry hunts.\n\n### Recognition\n\n| Stage | Core Temp | Signs |\n|-------|-----------|-------|\n| Mild | 90–95°F | Uncontrollable shivering, clumsiness, slurred speech |\n| Moderate | 82–90°F | Shivering stops, muscle rigidity, irrational behavior |\n| Severe | Below 82°F | Unconscious, no shivering, cardiac risk |\n\nThe most dangerous transition is from mild to moderate — when shivering stops, many people think they are warming up. They are not. The body has lost the ability to generate heat.\n\n### Field Treatment\n\n1. **Get out of wind and wet** immediately.\n2. **Remove wet clothing.** Insulate from the ground with a sleeping pad, pack, or branches.\n3. **Wrap the head** — significant heat loss occurs there.\n4. **Mild hypothermia**: If the victim is alert and shivering, give warm sweet fluids and actively warm with body heat and chemical heat packs.\n5. **Moderate/severe**: Handle gently — rough movement can trigger fatal cardiac arrhythmia. Keep the victim horizontal. Place heat packs in armpits, groin, and neck.\n6. **Never give alcohol.** It vasodilates peripheral blood vessels and accelerates heat loss.\n7. A hypothermic patient who appears dead may be resuscitatable — "not dead until warm and dead."\n\n### Prevention\n\n- Wool or synthetic base layers. **Cotton kills** — wet cotton loses approximately 90% of its insulation value.\n- Always carry a dry insulating layer regardless of the forecast.\n- A wind and rain shell weighs ounces and can save your life.\n\n## Altitude Sickness\n\nColorado elk hunts routinely happen at 9,000–12,000 feet. Wyoming''s Wind Rivers and Absarokas operate at similar elevations. If you are coming from sea level, altitude illness is a real risk.\n\n- **25% of visitors** sleeping above 8,000 feet in Colorado develop Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS).\n- **75% of people** from low elevation experience some symptoms above 10,000 feet without acclimatization.\n\n### What to Watch For\n\n**AMS (Acute Mountain Sickness)** — Headache plus one or more of: nausea, fatigue, dizziness, poor appetite, poor sleep. Onset is 2–12 hours after ascent. Treatment: stop ascending, rest, hydrate, take ibuprofen. Descend if no improvement in 24 hours.\n\n**HAPE (High-Altitude Pulmonary Edema)** — Fluid in the lungs. Shortness of breath at rest, persistent cough (possibly pink or frothy), blue lips, extreme weakness. **Fatal in 50% of cases without treatment.** Immediate descent of at least 3,300 feet or until symptoms resolve.\n\n**HACE (High-Altitude Cerebral Edema)** — Brain swelling. Confusion, loss of coordination (the "drunk walk" test), extreme lethargy, coma. **Immediate descent. Activate your SOS device.**\n\n### Prevention for Western Hunters\n\n1. **Arrive early.** Spend 2–3 nights at 8,000–9,000 feet before pushing higher.\n2. **Above 8,000 feet**, gain no more than 1,000 feet of sleeping elevation per day.\n3. **Hydrate aggressively** — respiration at altitude increases water loss significantly.\n4. **Avoid alcohol and sleeping pills** for the first 48 hours — both suppress respiration.\n5. **Avoid strenuous exertion** in the first 24 hours at a new elevation.\n6. **Consider Acetazolamide (Diamox)** — a prescription drug that speeds acclimatization. Discuss with your physician before the hunt.\n\n## Satellite Communicators\n\nIn remote western terrain, your phone will not have service. A satellite communicator is not optional for serious backcountry hunts.\n\n| Feature | Garmin inReach Mini 2 | SPOT Gen4 |\n|---------|-----------------------|-----------|\n| Price | ~$350 | ~$150 |\n| Monthly plan | $14.99+ | $11.95+ |\n| Network | Iridium (global) | Globalstar (gaps in remote areas) |\n| Two-way messaging | Yes | No (one-way only) |\n| SOS | Yes (GEOS 24/7) | Yes (GEOS 24/7) |\n| Weather forecast | Yes | No |\n\nThe inReach Mini 2 is the clear choice for backcountry hunters. Two-way messaging means you can communicate your situation to rescue coordinators without committing to a full SOS activation. The Iridium network has better coverage in deep canyons and dense timber than Globalstar.\n\n## When to Self-Rescue vs. Activate SOS\n\n**Activate SOS when:**\n- Arterial bleeding not controlled with a tourniquet\n- Suspected spinal injury (fall from height, unconscious)\n- Gunshot wound — any gunshot requires rapid evacuation\n- HAPE or HACE symptoms\n- Severe hypothermia (unconscious, no shivering)\n- Femur fracture (high blood loss risk even without visible bleeding)\n- Patient deteriorating despite treatment\n\n**Self-rescue may be appropriate when:**\n- Bleeding is controlled and the wound is manageable\n- The patient is alert, oriented, and physically able to move\n- Walking out in 2 hours is faster than waiting 7+ hours for SAR to reach your location\n- Injury is an isolated sprain or minor laceration\n\n**Key principle**: Stabilize before moving. Walking out is almost always faster than waiting for rescue — but movement can worsen spinal injuries and increase blood loss from unstable fractures.\n\n## Emergency Action Plan\n\nBefore every backcountry hunt, create a plan and leave it with someone at home:\n\n1. **Where you will be** — GPS coordinates of camp, trailhead, and planned hunting areas.\n2. **When you will return** — specific date and time.\n3. **When to worry** — how many hours overdue before they should contact SAR.\n4. **Your satellite communicator number** — so they can message you before escalating.\n5. **Vehicle description and location** — trailhead parking, license plate.\n\n## Training\n\n- **Stop the Bleed** — free 2-hour course on hemorrhage control. Widely available through hospitals and fire departments.\n- **Wilderness First Aid (WFA)** — 16-hour weekend course. The ideal minimum for backcountry hunters.\n- **Wilderness First Responder (WFR)** — 70–80 hour course. Recommended for guides, outfitters, or hunters doing extended solo trips.\n\nNOLS Wilderness Medicine and Wilderness Medical Associates are the most recognized certifying organizations.',
  10, 'basic', 'regulations-safety', 6, true, NOW()
),
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'Public Land Access and Navigation Rules',
  'public-land-access',
  'How public land access works in the West — BLM, National Forest, state trust land, corner crossing, and walk-in programs.',
  E'# Public Land Access and Navigation Rules\n\nIn the West, public land is the backbone of hunting opportunity. But not all public land is created equal — access rules vary by land type, state, and sometimes by individual parcel. Knowing what you can and cannot do on each type of land is the difference between a great hunt and a trespassing citation.\n\n## Federal Land Types\n\n### BLM (Bureau of Land Management)\n\nBLM manages 245 million acres across 12 western states. The default posture is **open to hunting** unless specifically posted closed — over 99% of BLM land is huntable.\n\n- No special permit required beyond your state hunting license.\n- State regulations govern season dates, species, and methods — BLM does not issue its own hunting rules.\n- Camping: 16-day maximum in one location, then you must move at least 25 miles or wait 30 days.\n- BLM actively manages 43 million acres of elk habitat, 131 million acres of mule deer habitat, and 23 million acres of bighorn sheep habitat.\n\n**The catch**: Approximately 9.52 million acres of western BLM land is landlocked — surrounded by private land with no legal road access. This represents 93% of all landlocked public land in the West.\n\n### USFS (National Forests)\n\nThe Forest Service manages 193 million acres, with approximately 99% open to hunting. Same principle as BLM: open unless specifically signed closed (around developed campgrounds, administrative facilities, etc.).\n\n- State hunting license is all you need.\n- Off-road motorized vehicle use is prohibited except in designated areas — check the Motor Vehicle Use Map (MVUM) for your specific forest.\n- Regulations can vary between individual forests, so verify with the local ranger district.\n\n### National Parks (NPS)\n\nThe opposite default: **closed to hunting** unless specifically opened. Some National Preserves allow hunting, but standard National Parks do not. This is not viable hunting ground.\n\n## State Trust Land — The Confusing One\n\nState trust lands were granted to states at statehood to generate revenue for public schools. Their primary obligation is revenue generation, not public recreation — and access rules vary dramatically.\n\n| State | Default Access | How to Get In |\n|-------|---------------|---------------|\n| Colorado | **Closed** by default | CPW''s State Trust Lands program opens ~973,000 acres (Sep–Feb). Use the STL Finder at cpw.state.co.us |\n| Montana | Open with license | A valid hunting license grants access to DNRC-managed trust lands |\n| Wyoming | Open with license | 3.6 million acres accessible with a valid Wyoming license |\n| Idaho | Open | 96%+ of state endowment lands are publicly accessible. Free camping up to 14 days |\n| Utah | Open with license | Access agreement between Trust Lands Administration and Utah DWR (through ~2032) |\n| Arizona | Open for hunting only | Your hunting license serves as your trust land access permit — but camping or hiking requires a separate Recreation Permit |\n\n**The takeaway**: In Colorado, assume state trust land is closed unless you can confirm it is in the CPW access program. In Montana and Wyoming, your license is your access pass. Always verify before walking in.\n\n## Corner Crossing — The Landmark Ruling\n\nCorner crossing is when you step from one parcel of public land to a diagonally adjacent public parcel, physically crossing only the single point where four ownership corners meet — two public and two private. You never set foot on private land.\n\n### The Iron Bar Ranch Case\n\nIn 2020–2021, four hunters in Carbon County, Wyoming used a stepladder to cross from BLM to BLM at a corner point without touching the Iron Bar Ranch. The ranch — spanning 50 square miles with 27 public parcels interspersed — sued.\n\nThe legal journey:\n- **2022**: County jury found the hunters **not guilty** of trespassing.\n- **May 2023**: Federal district court ruled in favor of the hunters.\n- **March 2025**: The 10th Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed — corner crossing is legal.\n- **October 2025**: The U.S. Supreme Court **declined to hear the appeal**. The ruling stands.\n\nThe legal foundation is the **Unlawful Inclosures Act of 1885** — originally passed to prevent cattle barons from fencing off public land. The court held that it supersedes inconsistent state laws.\n\n### Where Corner Crossing Is Legal Now\n\n- **Definitively legal** in all six 10th Circuit states: **Wyoming, Colorado, Utah, Kansas, Oklahoma, New Mexico**.\n- The ruling unlocked approximately **2.44 million acres** in Wyoming alone that were previously inaccessible.\n- **Legally uncertain** in 9th Circuit states: **Montana, Idaho, Nevada, Oregon, Washington**. No definitive ruling has been issued.\n\n**If you corner-cross**: Document your route with GPS. Do not physically touch private land. Understand that you are near private property and behave accordingly.\n\n## Walk-In Access Programs\n\nSeveral western states run programs that compensate landowners for allowing public hunting access on private land. These are free to hunters and can unlock enormous acreage.\n\n### Montana — Block Management Program (BMP)\n- Approximately **1,200 landowners** enrolled, covering roughly **6.8 million acres**.\n- Some BMAs require stopping at the ranch headquarters for a permission slip; others are open walk-in.\n- BMA guide published each fall — boundaries and requirements change annually.\n\n### Wyoming — Access Yes!\n- Two components: Walk-In Hunting Areas (WIHA) and Hunter Management Areas (HMA).\n- WIHAs are open to anyone with a valid license — no permission slip needed. Over 660,000 acres enrolled.\n- Total program: **2.5+ million acres** in enrolled boundaries, plus 190,000 acres of otherwise inaccessible public land adjacent to enrolled parcels.\n\n### Colorado — Walk-In Access (WIA)\n- Properties open seasonally for fall through spring hunting.\n- Walk-in only (no motorized access).\n- Some properties allow big game; others are limited to small game, waterfowl, and furbearers.\n- CPW publishes WIA maps annually.\n\n### Idaho\n- Landowner Appreciation Program (LAP) provides additional tags to landowners who allow public access — an indirect incentive rather than a formal walk-in system.\n\n## Identifying Land Ownership\n\nYou cannot rely on fences, signs, or assumptions. Modern mapping tools are essential:\n\n- **onX Hunt** is the industry standard — color-coded boundaries distinguishing BLM, USFS, state land, and private parcels. Displays landowner name, tax address, and acreage. Includes layers for Block Management, WIHAs, WIA properties, and more.\n- **GOHUNT Insider** and **BaseMap** are viable alternatives.\n- All these tools offer offline maps — download your hunt area before you lose cell service.\n\n### Practical Steps Before Every Hunt\n\n1. **Verify land ownership** on your mapping app before you walk in. Trust the color overlay, not your instincts.\n2. **Check state trust land status** — especially in Colorado, where the default is closed.\n3. **Download the current walk-in access guide** for your state. Boundaries change annually.\n4. **For landlocked public land**: Confirm legal access via a road easement, navigable waterway, or (in 10th Circuit states) a confirmed corner crossing before entering.\n5. **Print a backup**. Phones die. Paper maps and a compass remain the most reliable navigation in the backcountry.\n\n## Tribal Land\n\nTribal lands are sovereign territory. They are not public land, and state hunting licenses do not apply. Some tribes issue their own hunting permits to non-members — but this varies by tribe and must be arranged directly with the tribal government. Entering tribal land to hunt without explicit authorization is trespassing under federal law.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Download onX Hunt or a similar mapping tool and familiarize yourself with the land ownership overlay for your hunt area.\n2. Check whether your target state has a walk-in access program — it may open private land opportunities you did not know existed.\n3. If you are hunting in a 10th Circuit state with checkerboard ownership, study the corner-crossing ruling and plan your access routes with GPS documentation.\n4. Contact the local ranger district or BLM field office if you have questions about specific road closures, motorized restrictions, or seasonal access changes.',
